<p>
The Petri net library provides a matrix representation of dimensioned Petri nets. In a dimensioned
Petri net a unit of measurement is associated with the net's places.

<p>
A Petri net is a tuple
(<math>
  <mi>P</mi>
</math>,
<math>
  <mi>T</mi>
</math>,
<math>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&plus;</mi>
  </msup>
</math>,
<math>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msup>
</math>)

with 
<ul>
<li>
<math>
  <mi>P</mi>
</math>
a set of places,
</li>
<li>
<math>
  <mi>T</mi>
</math>
a set of transitions,
</li>
<li>
<math>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&plus;</mi>
  </msup>
</math>
a matrix of the form
<math>
  <mi>P</mi>
  <mo>&times;</mo>
  <mi>T</mi>
  <mo>&rarr;</mo>
  <mi>&Nopf;</mi>
</math>
called the post matrix, and
</li>
<li>
<math>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msup>
</math>
a matrix of the form
<math>
  <mi>P</mi>
  <mo>&times;</mo>
  <mi>T</mi>
  <mo>&rarr;</mo>
  <mi>&Nopf;</mi>
</math>
called the pre matrix.
</li>
</ul>


<p>
A Petri net's state is defined by its marking. A marking
<math>
  <mi>m</mi>
</math>
is a vector
<math>
  <mi>P</mi>
  <mo>&rarr;</mo>
  <mi>&Nopf;</mi>
</math>.

For any place
<math>
  <mi>p</mi>
  <mo>&isin;</mo>
  <mi>P</mi>
</math>
value
<math>
  <msub>
    <mi>m</mi>
    <mi>p</mi>
  </msub>
</math>
is the number of <it>tokens</it> in that place.

<p>
A Petri net changes state by firing transitions. 
Given a marking
<math>
  <mi>m</mi>
</math>,
firing a transition
<math>
  <mi>t</mi>
  <mo>&isin;</mo>
  <mi>T</mi>
</math>
is enabled when 
<math>
   <msubsup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mrow>
      <mi>p</mi>
      <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msubsup>
  <mo>&ge;</mo>
  <msub>
    <mi>m</mi>
    <mi>p</mi>
  </msub>
</math>
for each
<math>
  <mi>p</mi>
  <mo>&isin;</mo>
  <mi>P</mi>
</math>.
When the transition fires it consumes 
<math>
   <msubsup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mrow>
      <mi>p</mi>
      <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msubsup>
</math>
tokens from each place, and produces
<math>
   <msubsup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mrow>
      <mi>p</mi>
      <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mi>&plus;</mi>
  </msubsup>
</math>
tokens for each place.





<p>
In a matrix setting it is natural to define firing of transitions in parallel.
Given a transition vector
<math>
  <mi>x</mi>
</math>
of type
<math>
  <mi>T</mi>
  <mo>&rarr;</mo>
  <mi>&Nopf;</mi>
</math>
where
<math>
  <msub>
    <mi>x</mi>
    <mi>t</mi>
  </msub>
</math>
is number of times transition
<math>
  <mi>t</mi>
  <mo>&isin;</mo>
  <mi>T</mi>
</math>
fires, the new marking 
<math>
  <mi>m</mi>
  <mi>'</mi>
</math>
is given by

<blockquote>
<math>
  <mi>m</mi>
  <mi>'</mi>
  <mo>=</mo>
  <mi>m</mi>
  <mo>+</mo>
  <mi>F</mi>
  <mi>x</mi>
  <ms>
</math>
under the condition that
<math>
  </ms>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msup>
  <mi>x</mi>
  <mo>&ge;</mo>
  <mn>0</mn>
</math>
</blockquote>

where flow matrix
<math>
  <mi>F</mi>
</math>,
is defined as
<math>
  <mi>F</mi>
  <mo>=</mo>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&plus;</mi>
  </msup>
  <mo>-</mo>
  <msup>
    <mi>F</mi>
    <mi>&minus;</mi>
  </msup>

</math>